<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="release-planning">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-manager</domain>
    <summary>Structured approach to bundling, scheduling, and communicating product releases across cross-functional teams with per-function readiness verification and frozen manifests.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>release-planning</tag>
      <tag>release-management</tag>
      <tag>product-coordination</tag>
      <tag>readiness-gate</tag>
      <tag>cross-functional</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>release-coordination</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Release Planning</title>
    <summary>Structured approach to bundling, scheduling, and communicating product releases across cross-functional teams. Defines what ships, when, to whom, and how readiness is verified per function (eng, docs, support, marketing, legal) before deploy. The PM-flavored variant adds a release-readiness matrix (green/yellow/red per function with evidence URLs) on top of basic engineering deploy mechanics — decoupling "code is done" from "release is ready".</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Chaotic releases stem from missing a per-function readiness gate and a frozen manifest. Without an explicit readiness gate, one unverified cell ships and creates incidents or mis-sold features. The PM-flavored variant adds a release-readiness matrix (green/yellow/red per function with evidence URLs) on top of basic engineering deploy mechanics — decoupling "code is done" from "release is ready".</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Multi-team release crossing engineering, support, sales-enablement, marketing, and legal.</item>
        <item>Releases with paying customers where breaking changes or deprecations are present.</item>
        <item>Release calendar has slipped twice in a row (signal: shrink contents, shorten cycle).</item>
        <item>Regulated or contractual deploy windows require customer-facing change-control artifacts.</item>
        <item>Pre-launch GTM coordination where sales decks, support macros, and pricing copy must sequence.</item>
        <item>Release-train cadence reviews where the PM owns whether the train left full or empty.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Trunk-based / continuous deployment with feature flags at scale — use a launch plan tied to flag percentages instead.</item>
        <item>Pure infra/refactor with zero customer-visible behavior change.</item>
        <item>Solo founder shipping to fewer than 50 users — git push + changelog post is sufficient.</item>
        <item>A/B experiments — use experimentation-design, not a ship date.</item>
        <item>Hotfixes for live incidents — use the incident-response runbook; release-planning deliberation kills time-to-mitigate.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Release Types">
      <rule>
        <statement>Classify every release as Major, Minor, Patch, or Hotfix before planning starts; the type determines ceremony level, communication scope, and rollback complexity.</statement>
        <rationale>Type-based ceremony prevents over-engineering patch releases and under-preparing major ones. Hotfixes skip the normal process entirely and use the incident-response runbook.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Major: quarterly, large features, breaking changes, high risk. Minor: monthly, new features, medium risk. Patch: weekly or as needed, bug fixes, low risk. Hotfix: immediate, critical fixes, bypass release planning.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Step 1: Define Release Goals">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every release must have a primary outcome, a success metric, and optionally a theme before contents are selected.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a goal, "what should go in this release" has no forcing function. Features get added by availability rather than coherence.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Step 2: Select Release Contents">
      <rule>
        <statement>Include only completed features meeting definition-of-done, related bug fixes, documentation updates, and configuration changes. Exclude half-finished features and unrelated fixes.</statement>
        <rationale>Scope creep at release time is the leading cause of delayed deploys. Feature freeze 24-48 hours before deploy prevents last-minute additions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Apply a feature freeze 24-48 hours before the planned deploy; no new items after freeze without explicit PM exception logged in the release exceptions log.</statement>
        <rationale>Post-freeze additions bypass the readiness gate and introduce untested surface area into the release.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Ship "one more thing" after feature freeze because it is "already built".</description>
        <reason>Late additions bypass the readiness matrix and are the most common source of post-release regressions.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Step 3: Assess Release Readiness">
      <rule>
        <statement>Gate release on a per-function readiness matrix (eng, docs, support, marketing, legal, GTM). Green requires an evidence URL. Yellow and red require a named owner and blocker.</statement>
        <rationale>A "release plan complete" status that masks yellow/red cells ships unready features. Evidence URLs make green cells falsifiable, not aspirational.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Readiness Matrix Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>For every customer_visible=Y manifest item, build a readiness row per function (eng, docs, support, marketing, legal, sales-enablement, infra) with columns: artifact (specific deliverable), owner (named person), status (green/yellow/red/n/a), and evidence_link (URL required for green).</statement>
        <rationale>Vague status columns ("done", "in progress") hide the actual blocking condition. Named owners with specific deliverables make accountability legible across functions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Refuse to mark a cell green without an evidence_link URL pointing to the deliverable. Yellow and red cells must include a blocker description and expected-resolution date.</statement>
        <rationale>A green cell without evidence is a vote, not verification. The evidence URL is the only thing that distinguishes "someone said it's done" from "it is done".</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Step 4: Plan Communication">
      <rule>
        <statement>Tag every manifest item as customer_visible (Y/N) and breaking_change (Y/N). Items with customer_visible=N skip the comms loop entirely.</statement>
        <rationale>Applying the full comms plan to infra-only releases inflates PM workload without customer benefit. The boolean forces deliberate opt-in per item.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Steps 5-6: Execute and Post-Release">
      <rule>
        <statement>Deploy Monday through Wednesday; never deploy on Fridays or before holidays without a documented exception in the release exceptions log.</statement>
        <rationale>Friday deploys reduce the on-call response window and increase incident blast radius. Documented exceptions create an audit trail for policy decay detection.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Monitor metrics for 24 hours post-deploy. Hold a post-release retrospective; outputs update the next release's risk register with named owners.</statement>
        <rationale>Retrospective outputs tied to the next release's risk register turn one-off incidents into systemic improvements rather than forgotten post-mortems.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Four Agentic Loops">
      <p>The PM-flavored release pipeline runs as four sequential loops, each gated by human signoff before the next starts.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Loop 1 (Contents-freeze): agent reads tracker for status=ready-for-release AND fixVersion=vX.Y.Z, cross-checks CI green, merged PRs, DoD checklist, and migration rollback scripts. Outputs manifest.md with BLOCKED flags for failing items. PM reviews; manifest is frozen.</statement>
        <rationale>Automated DoD lint prevents the common failure of items marked "ready" without all criteria met. BLOCKED items stay in the manifest for PM to decide on, not silently removed.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Loop 2 (Readiness-matrix): agent builds the per-function readiness matrix from the frozen manifest. Yellow/red cells block until reviewed by PM.</statement>
        <rationale>Blocking on yellow/red before deploy prevents the readiness matrix from becoming a documentation exercise rather than a gate.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Loop 3 (Notes-and-comms): at T-1, agent generates three artifacts: customer-facing release notes, internal eng release summary, sales/support enablement brief. PM edits; never auto-publishes.</statement>
        <rationale>Three distinct audiences require three distinct registers. Auto-publishing release notes is the highest-trust-cost mistake a PM can make.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Loop 4 (Post-release retro): T+24h to T+7d, agent pulls deployment metrics, error-rate deltas, support-ticket spikes, and drafts a retro doc. PM holds a 30-min retro; outputs feed the next cycle's risk register.</statement>
        <rationale>Closing the feedback loop from deploy to next-release risk register converts incidents into institutional memory rather than forgotten post-mortems.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Release Notes Anti-Fluff Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Ban the following tokens from all customer-facing release notes: "excited", "delighted", "thrilled", "powerful", "seamless", "next-gen", "revolutionary". Lint output and regenerate on any hit.</statement>
        <rationale>Marketing tone erodes changelog trust. Customers who read changelogs want accuracy including known issues; over-polished notes signal hiding.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Treat Known Issues as a required section, not an optional admission. Absence of known issues for two releases in a row is a smell, not a victory.</statement>
        <rationale>Changelogs that admit limits build more trust than ones that don't. Customers who find issues not listed in the changelog report them as bugs, not limitations.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Generate release notes from a manifest captured at T-3 days and ship without regenerating at T-1.</description>
        <reason>Late-landing PRs and last-minute cuts make T-3 manifests stale. Always regenerate from the source of truth (merged-PR labels) at deploy time.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Common Failure Modes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Train-the-monster: monthly release trains accumulate too much scope; one feature slips and the whole train slips.</description>
        <reason>Large trains make pull-or-postpone tradeoffs painful at the last minute. Counter: smaller trains with feature flags decouple readiness from ship date.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Communication-plan inflation: PM builds a matrix of every audience × every channel × every revision for every release.</description>
        <reason>Most rows produce zero customer behavior change. Cut to channels where engagement can be measured; delete the rest.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Rollback theater: every plan documents "Rollback Plan: revert PR" without ever drilling it in staging.</description>
        <reason>First real rollback fails and discredits the PM. Drill rollback in staging at least quarterly with the on-call who would execute it.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Release notes written at release start and edited manually through the cycle rather than generated from merged-PR labels at deploy time.</description>
        <reason>Manual notes drift from reality as PRs land and cuts happen. Stale notes ship inaccurate and surface as customer trust incidents.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>PM as deploy gate: PM treats the release plan as a veto over engineering deploy mechanics.</description>
        <reason>Engineering owns deploy mechanics. The PM owns external readiness. Conflating the two makes the PM the bottleneck and erodes cross-functional trust.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Hidden dependencies: a feature depends on a back-office migration or vendor contract renewal not tracked in the engineering tracker.</description>
        <reason>Dependencies not in the manifest look green but are actually red. Mandate a cross-team dependencies section with a named owner per row.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Breaking-change detection delegated entirely to LLM agents reading PR titles.</description>
        <reason>Agents miss implicit breaking changes (default value flipped, undocumented header now required). Breaking-change rows must be human-asserted.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Cycle time tracked only as "ship-date hit-rate" rather than median feature commit-to-live time.</description>
        <reason>Ship-date hit-rate hides the truth: teams ship smaller things slower over time. Cycle time trend is the leading indicator of release health.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Recommended Subagents">
      <p>faion-mlp-impl-planner-agent — owns the contents-freeze loop: reads the tracker, validates definition-of-done per ticket, builds the manifest, refuses to include items that fail the DoD lint.</p>
      <p>faion-sdd-executor-agent — for any SDD task carrying a release-blocker label, the executor reads release-readiness.md and refuses to mark the parent feature done until every readiness cell for that feature is green or has a documented exception.</p>
      <p>faion-pm-agent (sibling under product-manager skill) — generates the readiness matrix and stakeholder-specific comms drafts; cites the source PRD and ticket history for every claim it makes.</p>
      <p>faion-marketing-manager / faion-gtm-strategist — consumes the manifest to produce launch-day assets (blog post, social copy, analyst brief). Subordinate to PM signoff; never auto-publishes.</p>
      <p>faion-content-marketer — drafts the customer-facing release notes from PR descriptions and ticket summaries, with explicit instructions to preserve known-issues honestly.</p>
      <p>password-scrubber-agent — non-negotiable before any release-readiness doc, manifest, or retro lands in a public repo or customer-facing channel. Release plans frequently embed customer names, internal URLs, vendor-contract details.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <p>Write the release notes before the readiness matrix is green. If you cannot describe the release to a customer in one paragraph, the scope is wrong; cut, don't pad.</p>
      <p>Force a customer_visible boolean on every manifest item. Items with customer_visible=N skip the comms loop entirely; this halves PM workload on infra-heavy releases.</p>
      <p>Make definition-of-done per item, not per release. A "release-wide DoD" hides items that never met theirs and shipped anyway.</p>
      <p>Track cycle time (commit → live for the median feature) per release and review the trend. PMs who only track ship-date hit-rate miss the truth: they are shipping smaller things slower.</p>
      <p>Run a pre-mortem two days before ship: "Imagine we are issuing a postmortem next week — what is it about?". Surfaces the dependency you forgot.</p>
      <p>Keep a release exceptions log separate from the readiness matrix. Each Friday-deploy, each yellow-shipped-anyway item, each comms-skip is a row. Review quarterly to spot policy decay.</p>
      <p>For B2B SaaS with named accounts, maintain a per-account release-impact view: which features land, which deprecations affect them, which migrations they must run. Drives the AM/CSM brief.</p>
      <p>Tie release retros to the next release's risk register. A regression caused by a missing flag becomes a "must have flag" entry in the next plan's risk row, with the named owner.</p>
      <p>Treat Known issues in customer notes as a feature, not a flaw. Customers trust changelogs that admit limits; absence of known-issues for two releases in a row is a smell, not a victory.</p>
      <p>Version the plan itself, not just the software. Plan v1 is the freeze-day artifact; plan v2 is the post-retro corrected version. Diff is the learning record.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Hallucinated PR contents — the agent invents a feature in the notes that does not exist in any merged PR.</description>
        <reason>Force every notes bullet to cite a merge SHA in an HTML comment; lint that the SHA exists in git log.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Auto-publishing release notes.</description>
        <reason>Never auto-publish. The agent emits a draft to a PR or doc; a human merges. One auto-publish of an inaccurate note destroys more trust than a year of well-edited drafts builds.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sycophantic marketing voice — LLMs default to "thrilled" and "delighted".</description>
        <reason>Add an explicit anti-fluff clause to the prompt and a post-generation lint that rejects drafts containing those tokens.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Breaking-change blindness — agents extracting notes from PR labels miss the implicit breaking change (a default value flipped, an undocumented header now required).</description>
        <reason>Require breaking-change rows to be human-asserted, not LLM-derived from PR titles.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Migration-script hallucinations — agents generate confident ALTER TABLE examples that drift from the actual migration.</description>
        <reason>Pull migration content from the migration files in the PR, not from the agent's interpretation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Stale manifest — an agent run at T-3 days that is not re-run at T-1 ships an obsolete manifest.</description>
        <reason>Make the manifest a CI artifact regenerated on every push to the release branch; consume the freshest only.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Comms-channel blast radius — agents posting drafts to a customer-visible Slack channel by mistake (typo in channel ID).</description>
        <reason>Restrict the agent's channel allowlist; require an explicit --channel arg, not a default.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Long-context manifest dumps — feeding the entire 200-row manifest into every prompt wastes tokens and dilutes attention.</description>
        <reason>Filter to customer_visible=Y for notes; filter to breaking_change=Y for migration guides. One filter per artifact.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Prompt injection via PR descriptions — a hostile or sloppy contributor pastes content into a PR description that the agent ingests verbatim into release notes.</description>
        <reason>Sanitize ingested text; never let agent-ingested PR text become customer-facing without human review.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Privacy bleed in retros — agents pulling support-ticket data into the post-release retro can inadvertently embed customer PII into a doc that goes wider than expected.</description>
        <reason>Run password-scrubber-agent on every retro; redact ticket bodies, keep only counts and categories.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Versioning drift — agent picks v1.2.3 from a tag that was never pushed; or picks v1.2.4 while a hotfix already claimed v1.2.4.</description>
        <reason>Always read tags from the upstream remote, never from local-only state; lint that the proposed version > all existing remote tags.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Cohort-flag mismatch — a release plan item names feature flag new-checkout but the deployed flag is checkout-v2.</description>
        <reason>Have the agent diff the manifest's flag-names column against the live flag-platform API; mismatch = hard fail.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Calendar-bound assumptions — "ship Tuesday" baked into prompts ages poorly across timezones, holidays, and frozen weeks.</description>
        <reason>Encode the deploy window as a date range from a calendar source, not a string in the prompt.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/release-plan.md" purpose="Full release plan template: metadata, goals, contents, risks, rollback, comms timeline"/>
      <template path="templates/release-notes.md" purpose="Customer-facing release notes template with required sections and anti-fluff rules"/>
      <template path="templates/release_readiness_lint.py" purpose="Script that validates the readiness matrix: green rows must have evidence URLs, yellow/red must have named owners"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-manifest-generation.txt" purpose="LLM prompt for contents-freeze loop: reads tracker, validates DoD, emits manifest"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-readiness-matrix.txt" purpose="LLM prompt for cross-functional readiness gate with evidence-link requirement"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-release-notes.txt" purpose="LLM prompt for customer-facing notes with anti-fluff discipline and required sections"/>
    </templates>
    <section name="CLI Tools for Release Automation">
      <p>gh (GitHub CLI): Build manifest from PR labels (gh pr list --label release-vX.Y.Z); auto-generate notes via gh release create --generate-notes. glab: GitLab equivalent for manifest + release-notes generation. git-cliff: Conventional-commit → changelog generator; backbone of automated release notes. release-please (Google): Automated release-PR generator from conventional commits; common for monorepos. semantic-release: Versioning + changelog + publish from commit messages; Node-centric but multi-language. changesets: Per-PR changeset files for monorepos (npm-heavy); decouples notes from commit messages. goreleaser: Go-binary release packaging + notes; widely used for CLI tools. linear-cli: Pull Ready issues into the manifest. jira-cli: Same for Jira-backed shops; filter by fixVersion. slack-cli: Post manifest, readiness summary, and retro draft to release channels. notion-cli: Sync the readiness matrix into the customer-facing roadmap page. mailmerge: Send per-customer or per-cohort release emails from a CSV (no marketing tool needed). kubectl / argocd / flux CLIs: Drive the actual deploy step from the release manifest (PM observes, eng owns). openfeature-cli / launchdarkly / flagsmith CLIs: Tie release plan items to feature flags; toggle by cohort. pandoc: Render notes to PDF for board reports / regulated-industry change-records.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Services and Integration Points">
      <p>GitHub Releases (SaaS): Default for OSS / dev-tool releases; generates notes from PR labels. GitLab Releases (SaaS / Self-hosted): Tight integration with milestones; first-class for regulated orgs. LaunchDarkly (SaaS): Feature-flag-driven release; PM defines cohorts, plan tracks % rollout. Statsig (SaaS): Flags + experiments + metric guardrails on release. Flagsmith (OSS / SaaS): Self-hostable flag platform; common in privacy-sensitive shops. Unleash (OSS): OSS feature-flag service; pairs with self-hosted release runners. Linear (SaaS): Cycle and Project map naturally to release manifest. Jira / Jira Service Mgmt (SaaS / DC): fixVersion is the canonical manifest filter; weak for cross-team gating. Productboard (SaaS): Public-facing roadmap + release notes for B2B SaaS. Aha! Roadmaps (SaaS): Built-in release manager + customer portal. Headway / Canny / FeedBear (SaaS): Customer-facing changelog widgets; embed release notes site-wide. Beamer (SaaS): In-app release announcement widget; pairs with notes pipeline. Statuspage / Statuspal (SaaS): Release windows = scheduled maintenance; declarative incident posts on regression. Sentry / Rollbar / Bugsnag (SaaS): Track release-tagged error rates; the post-release retro pulls from here. Datadog / Honeycomb / New Relic (SaaS): Release annotations on dashboards; correlate deploys with metric shifts. Argo CD / Spinnaker / Harness (OSS / SaaS): Progressive-delivery; PM plan items become rollout stages. PagerDuty / Opsgenie (SaaS): Auto-create release-watch incident; PM links from the plan. Confluence / Notion (SaaS): Default home for the human-readable plan; readiness matrix as a database. Mailchimp / Customer.io / Intercom (SaaS): Customer release-email orchestration; PM drafts copy, marketing automates send.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Manifest Generation Prompt Pattern">
      <p>You are a release-planning agent. Read the project tracker via API/CLI for items where status="ready-for-release" AND fixVersion="vX.Y.Z". Cross-check: CI green for the target branch (last 24h), All linked PRs merged, definition-of-done checklist complete (cite the DoD doc path), Migrations have a rollback script committed. For each item, output: ticket_id, title, owner, risk (L/M/H + 1-line rationale), customer_visible (Y/N), breaking_change (Y/N), feature_flag (name or "none"). Emit a manifest.md table; flag any item that fails any check as BLOCKED with the missing condition. Do not auto-remove blocked items; the PM decides.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Readiness Matrix Prompt Pattern">
      <p>Read manifest.md and the team-roster doc. For each customer_visible=Y item, build a readiness row with columns: function (eng | docs | support | marketing | legal | sales-enablement | infra), artifact (specific deliverable, not "ready"), owner (named person), status (green | yellow | red | n/a), evidence_link (URL to the doc/PR/ticket proving green; required for green). Yellow/red rows must include a blocker and expected-resolution-date. Output to release-readiness.md. Refuse to mark green without an evidence_link.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Customer-Facing Release Notes Pattern">
      <p>Read manifest.md and the merged-PR descriptions. Draft customer-facing release notes in this exact structure: # vX.Y.Z (YYYY-MM-DD), ## Highlights (1-2 sentences, plain English, no marketing adjectives), ## New (bullet per feature, what + why-it-matters, no codenames), ## Improved (bullet per change, observable user impact), ## Fixed (bullet per fix, link to public issue if any), ## Breaking changes (with migration steps, not just a warning), ## Known issues (be honest; workarounds where possible), ## Deprecations (timeline + replacement). Hard rules: No "we are excited" / "delighted" / "thrilled" filler. No internal codenames without a one-line gloss. If a section has no content, omit the header (do not write "None"). Cite the merge SHA per bullet in a hidden HTML comment for traceability. Output a draft for human review. Do not publish.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Sales/Support Enablement Brief Pattern">
      <p>From manifest.md, draft a one-page brief titled "vX.Y.Z — What changed for your customer". Sections: "What's new (user-facing)", "What to say if asked", "What to escalate", "Pricing/packaging changes (Y/N)", "Known limitations". Audience: a tier-2 support agent or an AE preparing for a renewal call. No engineering jargon; use customer-visible names only.</p>
    </section>
